04266nam a22006135i 9780271072418DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20211999pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710724187 a10.1515/97802710724182doi  a(DE-B1597)583919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a883.012231 aFoley, John Miles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHomer's Traditional Art /cJohn Miles Foley. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPronunciation Key -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: HOMER'S SIGN-LANGUAGE -- tPART II: HOMERIC AND SOUTH SLAVIC EPIC -- tPART III: READING HOMER'S SIGNS -- tPART IV: HOMERIC SIGNS AND ODYSSEY 23 -- tAfterword: -- tAppendix I. Feasting in Homer -- tAppendix II. "Deor" -- tNotes -- tMaster Bibliography -- tIndex -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent decades, the evidence for an oral epic tradition in ancient Greece has grown enormously along with our ever-increasing awareness of worldwide oral traditions. John Foley here examines the artistic implications that oral tradition holds for the understanding of the Iliad and Odyssey in order to establish a context for their original performance and modern-day reception.In Homer's Traditional Art, Foley addresses three crucially interlocking areas that lead us to a fuller appreciation of the Homeric poems. He first explores the reality of Homer as their actual author, examining historical and comparative evidence to propose that ";Homer"; is a legendary and anthropomorphic figure rather than a real-life author. He next presents the poetic tradition as a specialized and highly resonant language bristling with idiomatic implication. Finally, he looks at Homer's overall artistic achievement, showing that it is best evaluated via a poetics aimed specifically at works that emerge from oral tradition.Along the way, Foley offers new perspectives on such topics as characterization and personal interaction in the epics, the nature of Penelope's heroism, the implications of feasting and lament, and the problematic ending of the Odyssey. His comparative references to the South Slavic oral epic open up new vistas on Homer's language, narrative patterning, and identity.Homer's Traditional Art represents a disentangling of the interwoven strands of orality, textuality, and verbal art. It shows how we can learn to appreciate how Homer's art succeeds not in spite of the oral tradition in which it was composed but rather through its unique agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271072418zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271072418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271072418.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK